b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p2_sigma_pi" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Sigma and Pi Bonds</title>\n        <objref idref="bond_theory"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>In addition to the distance between two orbitals, the orientation of orbitals also\n            affects their overlap (other than for two s orbitals, which are spherically symmetric).\n            Greater overlap is possible when orbitals are oriented such that they overlap on a\n            direct line between the two nuclei. The diagrams below illustrates this for two p\n            orbitals from different atoms; the overlap is greater when the orbitals overlap end to\n            end rather than at an angle.</p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/sigma1.jpg" alt="Two diagrams are shown. Diagram a contains two molecules whose p orbitals, which are depicted as two balloon-shaped structures that meet together to form a peanut shape, are laid end over end, creating an area of overlap. In diagram b, the same two molecules are shown, but this time, they are laid out in a way so as to form a near-ninety degree angle. In this diagram, the ends of two of these peanut-shaped orbitals do not overlap nearly as much.">\n            <caption>(a) The overlap of two p orbitals is greatest when the orbitals are directed\n                end to end. (b) Any other arrangement results in less overlap. The dots indicate the\n                locations of the nuclei.</caption>\n        </image>\n        <p>The overlap of two s orbitals (as in H<sub>2</sub>), the overlap of an s orbital and a p\n            orbital (as in HCl), and the end-to-end overlap of two p orbitals (as in Cl<sub>2</sub>)\n            all produce sigma bonds (\xcf\x83 bonds), as illustrated below. A \xcf\x83 bond is a covalent bond in\n            which the electron density is concentrated in the region along the internuclear axis;\n            that is, a line between the nuclei would pass through the center of the overlap region.\n            Single bonds in Lewis structures are described as \xcf\x83 bonds in valence bond theory.</p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/sigma2.jpg" alt="Three diagrams are shown and labeled \xe2\x80\x9ca,\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cb,\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cc.\xe2\x80\x9d Diagram a shows two spherical orbitals lying side by side and overlapping. Diagram b shows one spherical and one peanut-shaped orbital lying near one another so that the spherical orbital overlaps with one end of the peanut-shaped orbital. Diagram c shows two peanut-shaped orbitals lying end to end so that one end of each orbital overlaps the other.">\n            <caption>Sigma (\xcf\x83) bonds form from the overlap of the following: (a) two s orbitals, (b)\n                an s orbital and a p orbital, and (c) two p orbitals. The dots indicate the\n                locations of the nuclei.</caption>\n        </image>\n        <p>A pi bond (\xcf\x80 bond) is a type of covalent bond that results from the side-by-side overlap\n            of two p orbitals, as illustrated below. In a \xcf\x80 bond, the regions of orbital overlap lie\n            on opposite sides of the internuclear axis. Along the axis itself, there is a node, that\n            is, a plane with no probability of finding an electron.</p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/sigma3.jpg" alt="Two peanut-shaped orbitals are shown, lying vertically and parallel with one another. They overlap one another along the top and bottom of the orbital.">\n            <caption>Pi (\xcf\x80) bonds form from the side-by-side overlap of two p orbitals. The dots\n                indicate the location of the nuclei.</caption>\n        </image>\n        <p>While all single bonds are \xcf\x83 bonds, multiple bonds consist of both \xcf\x83 and \xcf\x80 bonds. As the\n            Lewis structures suggest, O<sub>2</sub> contains a double bond, and N<sub>2</sub>\n            contains a triple bond. The double bond consists of one \xcf\x83 bond and one \xcf\x80 bond, and the\n            triple bond consists of one \xcf\x83 bond and two \xcf\x80 bonds. Between any two atoms, the first\n            bond formed will always be a \xcf\x83 bond, but there can only be one \xcf\x83 bond in any one\n            location. In any multiple bond, there will be one \xcf\x83 bond, and the remaining one or two\n            bonds will be \xcf\x80 bonds. These bonds are described in more detail later in this\n            module.</p>\n        <image src="../webcontent/sigma4.jpg"\n            alt="A diagram contains three Lewis structures. The left most structure shows an H atom bonded to a C l atom by a single bond. The C l atom has three lone pairs of electrons. The phrase \xe2\x80\x9cOne sigma bond No pi bonds\xe2\x80\x9d is written below the drawing. The center structure shows two O atoms bonded by a double bond. The O atoms each have two lone pairs of electrons. The phrase \xe2\x80\x9cOne sigma bond One pi bond\xe2\x80\x9d is written below the drawing. The right most structure shows two N atoms bonded by a triple bond. Each N atom has a lone pairs of electrons. The phrase \xe2\x80\x9cOne sigma bond Two pi bonds\xe2\x80\x9d is written below the drawing."/>\n        <p>As seen in the table on the previous page, an average carbon-carbon single bond is 347\n            kJ/mol, while in a carbon-carbon double bond, the \xcf\x80 bond increases the bond strength by\n            267 kJ/mol. Adding an additional \xcf\x80 bond causes a further increase of 225 kJ/mol. We can\n            see a similar pattern when we compare other \xcf\x83 and \xcf\x80 bonds. Thus, each individual \xcf\x80 bond\n            is generally weaker than a corresponding \xcf\x83 bond between the same two atoms. In a \xcf\x83 bond,\n            there is a greater degree of orbital overlap than in a \xcf\x80 bond.</p>\n        <example>\n            <image src="../webcontent/sigma5.jpg" alt="This figure shows a molecule composed of four carbon atoms. There is a double bond between carbons one and two and three and four, while a single bond holds carbon two and three together. Carbons one and four are also bonded to two hydrogens with a single bond while carbons two and three are each bonded to one hydrogen each by a single bond."/>\n            <p> Butadiene, C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>6</sub>, is used to make synthetic rubber. Identify the number of \xcf\x83 and \xcf\x80\n                bonds contained in this molecule. </p>\n            <p>There are six \xcf\x83 C\xe2\x80\x93H bonds and one \xcf\x83 C\xe2\x80\x93C bond, for a total of seven from the single\n                bonds. There are two double bonds that each have a \xcf\x80 bond in addition to the \xcf\x83 bond.\n                This gives a total nine \xcf\x83 and two \xcf\x80 bonds overall.</p>\n        </example>\n       \n        <wb:inline idref="sigma_pi_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n        \n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'